  "prompt": "Why does the sun rise in the east and set in the west but not the north and south?",
  "response": "The sun appears to rise in the east and set in the west because of the Earth's **rotation**. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Earth's Rotation:** Earth rotates on its axis from west to east. Imagine standing on Earth. As Earth spins eastward, you're carried towards the rising sun in the east. Later, as you rotate further, the sun appears to sink below the horizon in the west.\n\n*   **Why Not North and South?** The Earth's axis of rotation is tilted relative to its orbit around the sun. This tilt causes the seasons. If Earth's axis was perfectly perpendicular to its orbit, the sun would always rise due east and set due west everywhere on Earth.\n    *   **At the Equator:** Near the equator, the sun rises and sets almost due east and west throughout the year.\n    *   **Away from the Equator:** As you move away from the equator (towards the poles), the sunrise and sunset points shift gradually towards the north or south of east and west, respectively, depending on the time of year.\n\n*   **The Poles: The Extreme Case:** At the North and South Poles, the sun doesn't rise and set daily like it does elsewhere. Instead, there are long periods of daylight and darkness. For example, the North Pole experiences about six months of continuous daylight in summer and six months of continuous darkness in winter. During the summer, the sun circles around the sky, never setting, but remaining low on the horizon.\n\n**In short, the east-west movement of the sun is directly caused by Earth's rotation, while the seasonal north-south shift in sunrise and sunset positions is due to Earth's axial tilt.**",
